{
  "doc_id": "44147",
  "text": "Depression The stress of having a newborn hospitalized in the NICU raises a mother's risk for significant depressive symptoms. Although clinically significant depressive symptoms are common in the general population of mothers during their first 3 months postpartum (a meta-analytic review found a 19% prevalence rate; [CITATION_1] , between 28% and 67% of NICU mothers reported elevated levels of depressive symptoms [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Pinelli et al., 2008; [CITATION_5] . A longitudinal study suggests that these clinically significant levels of depressive symptoms persist: 63% of NICU mothers had elevated depression symptoms scores early on, when the infant was hospitalized; and at the 2-month, postbirth assessment, 30% still reported elevated symptoms [CITATION_6] . Furthermore, these depressive symptoms are severe. On the basis of limited data, approximately 33% of NICU mothers reported suicidal thoughts [CITATION_7] , a rate significantly higher than the 14% reported by postpartum women with nonhospitalized newborns [CITATION_8] .",
